<item>
  <title>Introducing openseespy-solvers</title>
  <dc:creator>Gustavo A. Araújo R.</dc:creator>
  <link>https://gaaraujo.github.io/posts/2026-06-06-openseespy-solvers/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<p>I released <a href="https://pypi.org/project/openseespy-solvers/"><code>openseespy-solvers</code></a>, a Python package that provides SciPy-style sparse linear and eigen solvers for OpenSeesPy’s <a href="https://opensees.github.io/OpenSeesDocumentation/user/manual/analysis/system/PythonSparse.html"><code>PythonSparse</code></a> system command.</p>
<p>The goal is simple: make it easier to experiment with solver backends while keeping the OpenSeesPy modeling workflow familiar.</p>
<section id="how-it-works" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="how-it-works">How it works</h2>
<div class="quarto-figure quarto-figure-center">
<figure class="figure">
<p><img src="https://gaaraujo.github.io/assets/images/posts/openseespy-solvers-python-solver.png" class="img-fluid figure-img" style="width:100.0%" alt="Schematic of OpenSees assembling residual and tangent matrices, passing them to a Python solver object, copying data to a GPU backend, solving for displacement increments, and returning the result to OpenSees."></p>
<figcaption>Conceptual workflow for connecting OpenSeesPy’s <code>PythonSparse</code> interface to external Python solver backends, including GPU-enabled sparse solves.</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p>OpenSeesPy still owns the finite-element model, the implicit integration loop, and the element state determination. During each analysis step, OpenSeesPy assembles the residual vector and tangent matrix, then passes those arrays through <code>PythonSparse</code> to a Python solver object.</p>
<p>That solver object can call a CPU backend such as SciPy, or copy the assembled arrays to a GPU backend such as CuPy or NVIDIA nvMath. Once the backend solves for the displacement increment, the solver writes the result back to OpenSeesPy so the analysis can update the trial state, check convergence, and continue.</p>
</section>
<section id="install" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="install">Install</h2>
<p>The base package includes NumPy/SciPy CPU solvers and requires Python 3.12 or newer:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb1" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode bash code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb1-1"><span class="ex" style="color: null;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">python</span> <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">-m</span> pip install openseespy-solvers</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>If OpenSeesPy is not already installed in your environment, use the optional extra:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb2" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode bash code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb2-1"><span class="ex" style="color: null;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">python</span> <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">-m</span> pip install <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"openseespy-solvers[opensees]"</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Optional extras are available for UMFPACK and NVIDIA GPU backends:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb3" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode bash code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode bash"><span id="cb3-1"><span class="ex" style="color: null;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">python</span> <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">-m</span> pip install <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"openseespy-solvers[umfpack]"</span></span>
<span id="cb3-2"><span class="ex" style="color: null;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">python</span> <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">-m</span> pip install <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"openseespy-solvers[cuda12]"</span></span>
<span id="cb3-3"><span class="ex" style="color: null;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">python</span> <span class="at" style="color: #657422;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">-m</span> pip install <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"openseespy-solvers[cuda13]"</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>See the <a href="https://openseespy-solvers.readthedocs.io/en/stable/installation/">installation guide</a> for platform notes, especially for UMFPACK on Windows and CUDA environments.</p>
</section>
<section id="quick-example" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="quick-example">Quick Example</h2>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb4" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb4-1"><span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">import</span> openseespy.opensees <span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">as</span> ops</span>
<span id="cb4-2"><span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">from</span> openseespy_solvers.scipy <span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">import</span> spsolve</span>
<span id="cb4-3"></span>
<span id="cb4-4">solver <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> spsolve()</span>
<span id="cb4-5"></span>
<span id="cb4-6"><span class="co" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;"># after defining the OpenSeesPy model:</span></span>
<span id="cb4-7">ops.system(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"PythonSparse"</span>, solver.to_openseespy())</span>
<span id="cb4-8">ops.numberer(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"RCM"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-9">ops.constraints(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"Plain"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-10">ops.integrator(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"LoadControl"</span>, <span class="fl" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">1.0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-11">ops.algorithm(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"Linear"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-12">ops.analysis(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"Static"</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-13">ops.analyze(<span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">1</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>For eigen analysis:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb5" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb5-1"><span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">from</span> openseespy_solvers.scipy <span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">import</span> eigsh</span>
<span id="cb5-2"></span>
<span id="cb5-3">eigensolver <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> eigsh(tol<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="fl" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">1e-8</span>)</span>
<span id="cb5-4">eigenvalues <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> ops.eigen(<span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"PythonSparse"</span>, <span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">5</span>, eigensolver.to_openseespy())</span></code></pre></div></div>
</section>
<section id="solver-backends" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="solver-backends">Solver Backends</h2>
<p>The package currently wraps solver objects from:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/sparse.linalg.html"><code>scipy.sparse.linalg</code></a> for CPU sparse linear and eigen solves</li>
<li><a href="https://docs.cupy.dev/en/stable/reference/scipy_sparse.html"><code>cupyx.scipy.sparse.linalg</code></a> for GPU sparse workflows through CuPy</li>
<li><a href="https://developer.nvidia.com/nvmath-python">NVIDIA nvMath</a> for GPU direct sparse solves</li>
</ul>
<p>The documentation includes <a href="https://openseespy-solvers.readthedocs.io/en/stable/recommended-solvers/">recommended first choices</a> for static/transient linear solves and generalized eigenvalue analyses, plus examples for direct, iterative, and preconditioned workflows.</p>
</section>
<section id="links" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="links">Links</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://openseespy-solvers.readthedocs.io/en/stable/">Documentation</a></li>
<li><a href="https://pypi.org/project/openseespy-solvers/">PyPI</a></li>
<li><a href="https://github.com/gaaraujo/openseespy-solvers">Source code</a></li>
<li><a href="https://github.com/gaaraujo/openseespy-solvers/issues">Issues</a></li>
</ul>
<p>This is an early release, and I am especially interested in feedback from OpenSeesPy users working with larger sparse systems, eigen analyses, and GPU-enabled environments.</p>


</section>

